    <h1>History of Calculus</h1>
    <h2>General</h2>
    <p>
      Calculus is a branch of mathematics that deals with the study of rates of
      change. It is divided into two main branches: differential calculus and
      integral calculus.
      <ul>
        <li>
          Differential calculus: It deals with the study of the derivative and
          the differential of functions.
        </li>
        <li>
          Integral calculus: It deals with the study of the relation between the
          antiderivative and the integral of functions.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    <p>
      Calculus was first developed over the concept of infinitesimals, but their
      lack of rigour led to the development of other concepts such as limits and
      continuity. Based on these concepts, calculus became to be part of a
      broader branch of mathematics called analysis, which extends the results
      of calculus to objects other than numbers.
    </p>
